hantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> I'm getting to the level now that when I get hit it really hurts (39-40). I have a question on group tactics where you get an add. The warrior/puller has pulled a single in DL when he runs by another one that adds on. Normally I use entrance to attempt to mezz at the largest distance possible. I don't tash on the initial pull as I can't always get the mezz off in time before I'm getting hit. Five times in six that mezz goes just fine as everyone is assisting on the puller's main target. It is that one time in six where there is a problem. The mob usually comes over and starts hitting me. Most of the time I have Rune Shield up unless we have multiple healers. This gives me enough time to usually recover and use a chain stun (sometimes works and sometimes doesn't). The stun was resisted, and I was unable to get another spell off. On an add like this, what are some good tactics to use root/mezz, tash/mezz, tash/root, have the warrior hit all mobs at least a couple of times before shifting to the main target to possibly help me avoiding aggro all the time? I'm usually okay and actually rarely die, but there have been some close situations lately, and I would like to hear how others do this. <p>Caeelyena-39th High Elf Enchanter <BR>
Henathu-39th Vah Shir Beastlord <BR>
Raienu-20th Half Elf Bard</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/usolometheenchanter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Solome the Enchanter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#330000>(8/16/02 1:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> i been through the same situation.  I would mez one on a double pull, it was resisted, the best advice i can give, if you got a healer who is on top of thier game, just keep trying to pull off the mez, if you time it, you can regain your concentration and nail it.  NEVER RUN AROUND hehe, learned that the hard way.  but if you got a healer you can trust, i say keep trying to mez.<br>
<br>
<br>
Solome Planeswalker<br>
58 Enchanter<br>
Erollisi Marr <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uinsenchant.showPublicProfile?language=EN>insenchant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#330000>(8/19/02 2:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> Caeelyena just wanted to drop you a note and give you a little warning about rooting the mob.  Rooting the mob makes for crazy aggro.  The mob will ping pong between attackers driving your healer nutz.  If I was you I would root them till you get the feel of your group.  If its a good one that knows keeping you alive ensures life for the rest of the group then demem root and mem blur.  All your Mezzes have a certain blur element but never enough.  Mezz and blur and hopefully you will fall down far enough on the hate list.  AND dont sit down til melee has 3/4 down or u will get sit aggro).<br>
<br>
Good luck)  being a Enchanter is alot of fun.  Grab your mez guns and start shooting.<br>
<br>
Insenchant Lvl 60 Phantasmist<br>
Candyman of MT <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uskysooner.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skysooner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#330000>(8/20/02 4:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> I found that out about root. It just isn't worth the mana to cast it. Easier to find a good group. I also have figured out that hitting tash before mezz is not usually a great idea. Tash carries such a large taunt that they are often hitting on me before I mezz. A typical encounter is more like this now. <br>
<br>
Single pull, wait for the MA to achieve aggro and tash/slow at 80%. Don't sit down for 10 seconds or so.<br>
<br>
Double pull. Find out what the MA is hitting on, and attempt to mezz the other. If it doesn't work (about 1 in 5), try it again. By this time, if it doesn't work I'm usually getting beat on, so I spam my under attack key and that takes care of it with the MA switching targets. If possible, I color stun and then mezz but this is rarely successful at 42 as my color stun is just not long enough to recover, move away and then mezz. I think this will get easier at 44 with the longer color skew spell.<br>
<br>
Mem blur has been very ineffective even after being used twice on those 40 level mobs. The good thing is my defense is almost maxed now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I keep hearing players who aren't chanters talking about how cha helps mezzing. I thought it was only really effective on charms. I carry both int and cha gear on me and switch out the gear as needed.<br>
<br>
The key as always to not having problems is to get a good group.  <p>Caeelyena-42 High Elf Enchanter <BR>
Henathu-39 Vah Shir Beastlord <BR>
Raienu-20 Half Elf Bard</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ubreezerslowsem.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Breezer Slowsem</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#330000>(8/20/02 6:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> Also keep in mine at your level your probably going to die on a bad pull (3 to 5 mobs). Once you hit 43 or 44 mez we get resisted very little.<br>
<br>
<br>
Breezer <br>
44th lvl <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uwyndehemply.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wynde Hemply</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#330000>(8/21/02 12:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.zeetec.net/host//wynde/Deadani.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> If you get an add..tash/stun/mez...very easy..have rune up, once it's mezzed you'll have time to re rune. Have the cleric symbol you, etc. If you get more than one and you've got the third stun spell..chain them, back up after the longest stun is on, and aoe mez...that will usually catch all of them, if it doesn't then go back to stunning. Used that tactic in dl for a while...works like a charm. <br>
<br>
Also, once you get the third stun, you can just partner....sk/chanter works best imho as the sk can heal himself and if he knows what he is doing is an excellent taunter...have him pull with arrows, tash as it is coming towards you and have him immediately snare..then stun away..have him fear if you get a stun resist..got very good xp that way.  <p><html><center><font face="annifont"><font color="8b008b">Wynde Hemply</center><br><center>54th Illusionist</center><br><center>Alliance of the Griffin</center><br><center>Tholuxe-Paells</center><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=256113"><center>My Gear</center></a></font>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uskysooner.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skysooner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#330000>(8/21/02 9:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> I have found that if you do tash on the pull, you are less likely to get the mezz off in time due to the casting time and the speed of the mob. Tash/stun/mezz sounds like a very viable option for me. Luckily I already have the spell color skew through research, so I'll have a longer lasting chain stun spell to use. In a good team, we rarely get adds, but we were chain pulling and generally had one being hit on, one mezzed and one being pulled. I'm just about to ding 43, so I'm hoping the resist rate goes down. Right now it is about 2 in 7. Thank goodness for rune. <p>Caeelyena-42 High Elf Enchanter <BR>
Henathu-39 Vah Shir Beastlord <BR>
Raienu-20 Half Elf Bard</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umassagran.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Massagran</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#330000>(8/22/02 5:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dimestore.esmartweb.com/pages/skelwalk.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> i found that the easy way to control an add is to mezz it first. If mezz lands succesfully, just tash and slow. If it doesn't, use color flux (the lowest level one). You just have enough time to recast mezz. If done well, you stun and mezz, and only being hit once (no rune needed). But if stun or the second mezz is resisted, you should use another stun (color shift), tash, and then try to mezz again. <br>
 Also root is a good option if the mobs purchases you, but its better to learn how to use memblur (at higher levels, mobs can summon you, and that makes root useless). At 44 i think we have reocurring amnesia, which is a great single target memblur that saved my life some times... <p><b><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=87742">Massagran Menteaudaz</b></a>, lvl  55 Beguiler<br>
"<i>Massagran begins to cast a spell<br>
Girlfriend have been charmed.<br>-dejame jugar, solo 5 minutitos mas :-)<br>Your charm spell wore off.<br> Girlfirend hits YOU for 300dmg, bashes, stuns, nuke, laugh, YOU DIED</i>"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uskysooner.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skysooner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#330000>(8/22/02 8:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> Interesting you should mention just mezzing first. I talked with a high level friend of mine about groups he was in and tactics. He said he hardly ever saw the enchanter tash on a pull. Mezz has such a lower taunt than tash does. About one time in three a failed mezz will get the creature beating on me, and sometimes I can get a color line off, but it seems like many times I'm interrupted. This could just be the level (ding 43 btw). I think the best solution will be levels and the mezz resists should go down.<br>
<br>
Does anyone here think that AoE mezz is a good solution for more than one add? The couple of times I tried it (even with greens), I get a couple of resists and then I get nothing off. I have stopped using it for now. <p>Caeelyena-43rd High Elf Enchanter <BR>
Henathu-39th Vah Shir Beastlord <BR>
Raienu-20th Half Elf Bard</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub136.ezboard.com/ullientylln.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llientylln</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#330000>(8/26/02 10:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.prophesy.ca/eq/enchanters/Llientylln.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mezzing add tactics</span><hr size=1> I rarely use the ae-mez now - simply because the things I'm mezzing are over the dazzle cap and the fascination spell won't take hold. But, in areas where I know that is not the case, I will pull out the ae-mez as an emergency mez. Before it wears off, tash the adds so that there is lower chance of any resists on recast. When the pull breaks down to a manageable size, root the adds and let the ae wear off then pick them off with single mez. Works great if you end up with a nasty pull deep in Chardok or such.<br>
<br>
Personally, I almost never tash first when mezzing adds, it only leads to a mob beating on me before the mez can be cast. Stunning draws more agro than necessary, so I never use that outside of AE unless I'm fighting a caster that has an awful ae rain (ie., Tae Ew lifedrinker /shudder) - in which case its not related to trying to mez them at all so moot point.<br>
<br>
Root is a last resort for when the mez isn't landing and I need to get distance. Train your cleric well so that they will toss a root on the mob if they see you getting smacked too much (more mana efficient for them to toss out a root than to throw heals or rez you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   - but for pity sake don't let the druid root heh)<br>
<br>
I never ever ever ask the MT to switch (maybe because I often fight with an SK and bard and dotting the mob is a common practice). That only leads to more chaos and confusion (that random_melee_01 who went to grab a soda without saying anything was afk and didn't see the switch call..). It's our job to nail that add or adds down -- the only exception being the mobs that cannot be mezzed. Knowing which mobs require GoK, require Rapture or cannot be mezzed at all is key to being prepared for what's incoming (I have my own personal cheat-sheet on these and use it constantly so that I avoid nasty surprises when possible). <br>
<br>
I find that more often than not, I'm using GoK over dazzle, mana inefficient as it is, simply because of the short recast time. If it doesn't land, I can recast it by the time the fail message has hit. That usually lets me get two mez attempts in before the mob gets within melee range, if I'm in a good position to see the pull incoming. If I get resisted more than twice, boom rapture time. While its on the short-mez, quick tash and root and back away -- let rapture fall and switch to a more lasting and mana efficient mez. <br>
<br>
As for the int/cha issue .. I've tried to keep those balanced as I've leveled, so that now I'm at 250int/255cha (buffed) and got there in stages - not favoring one over the other. I personally believe in the &quot;cha is a factor&quot; camp, but I have no real proof either way, only gut reactions based on what I've seen out of the luck of the random number generator heh. Levels definitely are key on the resists. <br>
<br>
Anyhow, that was a longer post than I intended and I hope someone finds it slightly useful or informative heh.<br>
